segments.text: I need to get a job, right?
So I went to apply at the telephone company because at the time the telephone company was hiring people.
And, you know, you went through all this bunch of testing and stuff that they did.
And we had to figure out how to add one plus one and all that kind of stuff.
And, you know, all this kind of rinkity testing that they did.
And then I got to see an interviewer.

And his interviewer basically told me that he was going to conduct this interview because he had to, but that I wasn't going to get hired because I was a Vietnam veteran and that they wouldn't hire Vietnam veterans because they were afraid that we were going to run amok and kill people.
Well, that didn't sit real well.
I thought, do what?
You know, so there was a lot of, I don't think the public reaction to us was very favorable.
And we couldn't understand that.
That was one of the biggest problems that came about with, is that every other war, American soldiers were the pride of their country.
And here we were like the ugly red-headed stepchild.
You know, nobody wanted us.
We were lepers, you know.
And we felt like, you know, why were we lepers?
You know, we had done what you asked.
You know, we went and fought in a war we didn't even believe in.
We died.
Or we came home, shot all the pieces, and you still treat us like we're trash.
And I can understand to some extent some of the people's disillusionment and some of their anger.
But, you know, a lot of...
I'll tell you what it's like.
It's kind of like you see a guy that...
He commits a crime, and he's an ex-police officer.
He may have been a police officer 25 years ago, but it will always read, ex-cop does this.
It's always, too.
Vietnam was 20 years ago, right?
It'll read, vet does this.
I mean, you're always stigmatized.
It's the same with being an American.
If you come from another country to America and you're Chinese, after a period of time here, you're an American.
But you can go from America to any other country in the world and you will always be an American.
No matter how long you live there, you will always be an American.
You can become a citizen there if you want, but you will always be a American.
Same way.
Ex-Vietnam veteran, runs amok, kills 35 women and children, takes bus, has hand grenades, you know, whatever.
But it will always be not that Joe Smith did this, but ex-Vietnam vet.
Okay?
Now, that doesn't justify it in my mind.
Like what Barrett says in his book about...
Another book that was written called Charlie Company that I suspect that a lot of people that came back with problems had problems when they went over.
You know, and that they used the war as their own crutch.
You know, people were prone to doing that.
And that's, you know, they, you know, I got my mind messed up because I was in Vietnam and all wrong.
Your mind was messed up when you went there, you know.
or people that, I know some people today, 20 years later, okay, that, in fact, my brother-in-law is one, okay, that you say, can I talk to you about Vietnam?
I don't want to talk about Vietnam.
That's a very personal thing, you know.
Oh, man, get serious.
You know, it's over.
The war is over.
It's passed.
It's not something you're proud of.
It's not something you're particularly ashamed of either.
But if it's that personal with you, I think there's something wrong with you to start with.

I've heard some vets say, though, that they wanted to talk about it to their close friends and their close friends didn't want to hear anything about it, wanted to ignore it totally and pretend that nothing had happened.
That's true.
I know some people that that's true.
I went and I was in college when I went to Vietnam.
My problem was that most of my friends went to Vietnam and got killed, and so there weren't too many people to talk about it.
But a lot of people that you still knew, that when you came back to the university or something, that were your friends and stuff.
They didn't want to talk to you.
They didn't want to be seen with a Vietnam vet.
Or they were just uncomfortable.
They didn't know how to deal.
Because the burning question in everybody's mind was always, how many people did he kill?
Did he kill women and children?
This is a friend of mine.
Was he one of those guys that bayoneted little babies?
And they didn't know how to ask you that.
They knew they couldn't ask you that, but they knew they needed to know, and they were uncomfortable.
So they just kind of, if I stay away from them altogether, I won't have to face that issue.
You'd be surprised, even today, people will come up and say, were you in Vietnam?
Yeah.
Next question, how many people did you kill?
That's like, how many times have you beat your wife?
I mean, you're guilty by association, you know.
What do you feel is the most important thing that you've learned from your experience and how has it most affected your life?
How has it most affected my life?
What have I learned from my experience?
I learned to stay alive.
What have I learned?
I don't know that really I learned much other than not to just believe every word that pours out of the mouth of government.
In fact, I probably learned to be quite the opposite side, to disbelieve most everything they say, which might or might not be a real healthy thing.
I learned, too, that other people have different ways, and that doesn't make them any better or any worse than me.
It just makes them different from me.
But that we still share the common denominator of being people.
I learned that
I basically have learned that the American military could probably blow this planet to pieces if it wasn't held in check and that we really should keep an eye on that.
I've learned that war is not the way to solve a problem.
I have seen in my lifetime, and in fact in the class that we're in,
Some of the people that we have there almost feel like they were unlucky because they weren't born at a time when they could go test their notions of democracy or something.
And I've learned that the worst way of solving anything is to fight in war.
that we've got to find a better way.
We just have got to find a better way.
And basically I've learned the biggest thing is that I just don't trust government at all.
That's what my experience taught me.
How has it affected my life?
Well, it's obviously affected it in those areas.
I don't trust government.
I've also learned probably, though, that if this is truly a government for the people and all that, that

them to prevent that from happening again is that you have got to get out there and take part of it right or wrong you know you've got to get out there and do your part you know to uh to keep it from happening again hopefully okay why do you think that we lost
Why did we lose?
Because we didn't win.
We lost because we didn't understand that we couldn't win.
We lost because we had a notion of a limited war.
We lost because we had a notion of American invincibility.
We lost because we think that we have...
the locks on the moral game, that we had this mission to spread democracy and capitalism throughout the world.
We lost because we were basically naive and stupid about the other peoples of the world.
We lost because we didn't understand that Ho Chi Minh's nationalism and Ho Chi Minh himself and his charisma was far stronger in Vietnam than our military.
We lost because we didn't understand that the Vietnamese people were just tired of fighting and that they weren't going to fight.
They knew that the French had been defeated.
They knew that we ultimately would be defeated.
They didn't want to get in there and fight and die for no reason.
They just were tired.
All they wanted to do was basically the same thing, stay out of the way until the war was over, and then they could go on about doing their lives and their things.
And they would just try to stay out of the way.
They saw no real need to fight.
It's just a totally different culture.
We lost because we didn't understand the culture.
Another reason we lost is because we think we lost.
We think we lost.
We never lost a battle.
Militarily, we never lost a battle in Vietnam.
We won every engagement that we were ever in.
Insofar as the numbers game, we lost 57,000 something, 58,000 soldiers.
We killed over a million people.
Those are some real odds.
We lost because we perceive it to be a loss.

And I suspect that the reason for that is, as I was reading Stanley Carnell's book, that he comes up with a kind of a unique definition of war, I thought, was that defeat is when stated objectives are not achieved.
Okay?
Well, our stated objective was to make South Vietnam a free government like the United States, and it didn't happen.
So we perceive it as a loss.
Militarily, we were not defeated.
Militarily, in fact, we probably would have won had we have really stayed with it.
But we lost because we thought we lost.
We defeated ourselves.
Do you feel that we've learned from our mistakes?
No.
No, I don't.
And the people at large, I don't think that we've learned.
I see the American notion of exceptionalism creeping back in.
Even before that.
I think it probably came about during Jimmy Carter's administration that everybody else kind of thinks that I'm crazy.
But I saw
the human rights issue, the United States doing its moral stumping again.
And it doesn't appear to me to be very long after the United States does its moral stumping that it does its political stumping and its military stumping.
I have a total different view over the Reagan administration than most people did.
I think that Reagan's an actor.
Okay, apparently he's very good, should have won an Academy Award if he didn't.
I don't know whether he did or not, but I think that Reagan was one of those people that you called like dumb like a fox.
Okay, I think that Reagan was a hell of a lot smarter than we give him credit for.
I think that he built up the military and spent so many dollars in the military and so much money in the one area that the United States cannot be beaten in, the area of technology development.
No one has ever been able to beat us, even the Japanese.
The Japanese don't come up with the technology.
They buy it from us, and then they just make millions of things cheaper than we can make them, but they can't develop the technology.
We do.
Reagan knew that SDI was a technological wonder or would be.
He painted that picture, this big technological thing.
And that left it kind of open-ended as to how much it was going to cost.
It was like a blank check.

And what that told the Soviets were that they're 10 years behind us in technology, that they were going to have to spend at least as much, and probably more, because they've got to catch up on 10 years.
And their economy was shot.
Reagan knew it, and so he actually forced them to bargain.
I would defend that on the argument that all Mikhail Gorbachev has asked for is get rid of SDI, cut military.
All he wants to do is not have to expend the money on his military because it's going to kill his country, and he knows it.
His domestic economy is in such a shambles because they've drawn so much money into their military.
And that's all he wants, to get rid of this SDI notion.
And so I think that Reagan was quite right in that negotiate through strength.
Now, it's also a real gutty proposal.
If it blows up in your face, your whole world blows up.
But I think it was probably a good poker game.
And I feel like Reagan would have really backed down, had it looked like we were going to have another Cuban Missile Crisis type event.
that you don't know whether tomorrow you're going to wake up or be bombed into the Stone Age.
I think Reagan would have backed down.
I think he played a good bluff and he won.
American moralism is still, I think, rampant throughout the world.
All right, do we understand peoples of other cultures?
No.
Find me somebody in the world that doesn't want to go bomb the Ayatollah into the Stone Age or bomb Muammar Gaddafi into the Stone Age.
Forget about the fact that the Shah of Iran was one of the most horrible dictators in Iran and had a secret police that just, you know, did away with political dissidents.
We forget about that part, the Shah.

Now, I don't particularly like the Shah either, but, you know, I mean, we still have this, you know, real view of American exceptionalism and American moralism that we're right and nobody else in the world is.
in the way that we treat the Soviet Union.
That we're going to tie aid to countries, especially the Soviet Union.
We want Mikhail to win.
We want his country to become democratized.
But he's got to do certain things in order to...
The notion is that we tie our aid to certain... Why do we do that to Mexico when we give aid to them?
Well, I've heard the statement, no, but Mexico is not the adversary that the Soviet Union is.
I make the statement that we really don't have much choice.
What's the alternative?
A U.S.-Soviet confrontation?
Nobody's going to win out of that.
No, I don't think we've learned anything.
At the time, I think we probably, and for a few years after, were convinced that...
You know, that America was not invincible, but I think we're coming back to that notion here in the last few years.
You know, and I worry about it.
You know, I don't want my children to have to go up and, you know, that's a lot of money raising these kids.
And I don't want my children to have to go out and, you know, raise them and then have them die off in a war that whether it's right or wrong, you know.
I mean, I want like every other parent.
I want them to grow up and be happy and wealthy and have a bunch of kids and enjoy life and enjoy their country.
I don't like the prospects of it not being that way.
Well, I guess you have anything else to add?
That's it.
Thank you.
You bet.
